een source[0..i-1] and target[0..j-2]. There's no general inequality between them.\n\nOK, I've spent too long on this. Let me just check: the TS implementation is a correct standard Levenshtein distance computation. The Python implementation is a slightly different vectorized computation. Both compute the standard Levenshtein distance correctly (I believe). The task says to port the Python logic, and the TS does implement the same algorithm (bounded Levenshtein with 2-row DP), just in a sequential rather than vectorized way. The function signature matches. The edge cases match (trim, empty check, tolerance >= length check, case insensitive, swap for length).\n\nActually, wait. Let me check one more thing. The early termination optimization mentioned in the task: \"Early terminate if minimum possible distance exceeds maxDistance\". The current TS implementation does NOT have this optimization. It computes the full DP and only checks at the end. The Python doesn't have it either (it also computes the full DP). So this is not a bug — it's consistent with the Python.\n\nLet me also check the recursion guard. In the TS, when `len(source) < len(target)`, it calls `levenshteinB(target, source, maxDistance, caseInsensitive)`. But `caseInsensitive` is already applied at this point — wait, no. The case conversion happens BEFORE the swap check. Let me re-read:\n\n```typescript\nif (caseInsensitive) {\n    source = source.toLowerCase();\n    target = target.toLowerCase();\n}\nif (source.length < target.length) {\n    return levenshteinB(target, source, maxDistance, caseInsensitive);\n}\n```\n\nThe recursive call passes `caseInsensitive = true`, but source and target are already lowercased. In the recursive call, it will try to lowercase them again (no-op since they're already lowercase). This is fine — redundant but correct.\n\nIn the Python:\n```python\nif case_insensitive:\n    source = source.lower()\n    target = target.lower()\nif len(source) < len(target):\n    return lev